President Obama has declared a state of emergency in Minnesota due to severe storms and flooding that began on March 16, 2009. This declaration allows the Department of Homeland Security's Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) to coordinate disaster relief efforts and provide assistance to alleviate the hardship and suffering caused by the emergency. FEMA is authorized to mobilize resources and equipment to help the affected areas. Emergency protective measures, including direct federal assistance, will be provided with 75 percent federal funding. The counties of Clay, Kittson, Marshall, Norman, Polk, Traverse, and Wilkin are included in this declaration.